about 1528","1555":"1555","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","1552":"1552","1585":"1585","about 1554":"about 1554","1639":"1639","1528":"1528","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","England":"England","Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Powel","type":"FIRST","meanings":["The English form of the Welsh name Hywel."],"variants":[]},{"name":"“Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Transferred use of the Irish surname, Gaelic <i>Ó Tíghearnaigh</i> ‘descendant of Tighearnach’ (  see  Tighearnach   ). This is now also well established as a girl's name. Its use in North America is due in part at least to the influence of the film actress  Gene Tierney  (  1920–91 )."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Powel “Lord of Maermawr” Madog was born in 1525, in Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales as the son of Howel Ap Madoc and Margred Verch Ieuan. He married Mallt Fwyall Howell about 1549, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died in 1560, in Wales, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1525–1560":"1525–1560","1528–1585":"1528–1585","1543–Male":"1543–Surnud","1550–1639":"1550–1639","1552–Male":"1552–Surnud","1554–Male":"1554–Surnud","1555–Male":"1555–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1524–Female":"1524–Surnud","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1525":"1525","abt 1555":"umbes 1555","1524":"1524","about 1549":"umbes 1549","about 1528":"umbes 1528","1555":"1555","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","1552":"1552","1585":"1585","about 1554":"umbes 1554","1639":"1639","1528":"1528","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","England":"England","Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1525–1560":"1525–1560","1528–1585":"1